Polish enthusiasts devoted themselves to space flights before World War II; but they did not always meet with understanding.
For example, I will remind you of A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on 6 December 1933 represented ideas from his pioneering work Entering space.
The ideas of a young engineer (born 1905) left listeners cold and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Award for the Entry of Space in France.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote a number of books dedicated to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned space promoter and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the reverse side of the moon was named by his name.
As early as 1925, a railway crew was built in Poland, which was supposed to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and neither are the details of the project known.
It is neither clear whether the rocket was to be used for the launch of the drone or for its application.
Information about this division is known only from time print.
Since 1933, rocket missiles began to deal with Polish artillery.
The research provided the Cell of Arms Technology in cooperation with Professor Mieczyslaw Wolfek and Professor Gustaw Mokrzyckieg.
From preserved materials it is clear that research has reached the stage of practical tests.
However, research was interrupted by the coming of the German troops.
In 1937, a design of a photoelectric fighter rocket appeared in the professional press, designed by an engineer of Rohoziński, and in the following year the work of Rakiet - an air torpedo and a rocketomb of the airman of Levyw-Krzywobłocký came out.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Temporary Advisory and Science Committee) coordinated all the projects of military use of rocket technology.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity its activity ended the start of the war.
After the war in Polish press, other works dedicated to cosmonautics appear thanks to the work of the Polish astronaut Society.
For the first time, there is a mention of society in the November edition of the 1954 magazine Problems, in which there are four more comprehensive articles devoted to astronauts.
In one of them, since Prof. M. Subotowicz, it is proposed to create a company that will deal with cosmonautics.
By then, projects of artificial satellites had already started and it was clear that space research was a prospective field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish astronaut Society (PTA) has been trying to enter the International astronaut Federation (founded 1951) and in autumn PTA has become a proper member.
And in the following year, PTA President Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became Vice-President of the International astronaut Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been involved in the development of a very successful meteorological rocket RM (Measure rocket) that has become the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first start took place on 10 October 1958.
The 1800-meter rocket was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later an improved version of RM-1A was built and in the summer of 1959 the flight tests of two-stage RM-2 rockets were launched in the Bledov desert.
The rocket was 1.4 metres long and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
Another development type should already have been capable of real scientific work - RM-34 rocket should have reached 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the height wind.
However, in 1962, further developments were suspended.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965 became the successor to the first RM.
The rocket was designed as two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (labelled Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed that differed in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B with a volume of 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C with a volume of 0.62 litres.
The maximum access for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Air Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a starting mass of 380 kg and was able to carry a useful load of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
It is still necessary to mention Poland's entry to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
Poland was also involved in space research on Soviet artificial satellites under the Interkosmos programme and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimír Remkov.
