What is private offline is both private and online
Privacy.
According to the dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, it is something that is personal or "private life that everyone has the right to protect against any disturbance".
What is privacy for a person under 16?
How does this definition apply to everyday life and social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposed to when he publishes on the Internet issues that he would certainly not tell anyone during ordinary communication?
Reporters from elPeriodico confessed five boys and girls between 10 and 15 years old who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy as "something entirely own" in personal terms and as "user name and password" if it was a social network.
"My biggest secret I wouldn't publish," says Jorge, in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he's had accounts for two years.
"They are very secret secrets, my mother may know about them, but not the whole world," she says.
"I put pretty pictures on the FB or pictures we're playing.
I'm also talking to some friends there.
I wouldn't share a picture that wasn't mine or a picture that would make anyone laugh," she says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to publish obscene photographs, photographs of naked persons or photographs of crimes, or write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 of his friends on the FB and his nine supporters on Twitter.
Most of them are related.
There's a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
"I have set up an account on Twitter so I can express my views and write interesting contributions.
I don't know if anyone's gonna answer, I'm just putting them in there," he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far or fast to communicate with friends," he says.
Without hesitation, he says he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
This teenager owns accounts on the hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask networks and the last mentioned network admits that he does not know 20 people from his list of friends.
"I'm not afraid of it because we have something in common, for example music," he says.
According to this boy, none of them set him up or asked him for his address or phone number.
"If they insist on me or require me, I simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José applied to Ask after reading the recommendations on Twitter.
This boy is no stranger to what is now called cyberbullying.
"They blackmailed a friend on the social network.
They threatened him and asked for money.
He never knew who it was," he confirmed.
According to José, the victim didn't log out of the account.
"Only activated a private regime."
Then he explains a series of steps how to set up the account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would have posted photos of people known in awkward or embarrassing situations.
"Of course, I would have done it if I'd been uncomfortable or if I'd just wanted to.
Even though I know it's cyberbullying," he says.
Key questions
Marielos Porras, English teacher and graduate in the field of education and teaching, feels that children and adolescents in social networks must understand that the main objective of these networks is to inform them.
He states that "the Internet was created as a means of finding information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porrasová notes that academic worker Marc Prensky, a graduate of pedagogy at Yale University and author of an article digital natives and digital immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain this phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born at the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who need to be taught, while we are only learning," he says.
It explains that this is a complex topic, "because we ask them to discern what it is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what it is not, at the age when they are not mature."
Also, to be - as far as the surroundings are concerned - discreet, at a time when what they desire most is to be liked, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences", he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way is to show children and adolescents what privacy is, to ask questions that make them think.
"To tell them not to do something, it doesn't work," he adds.
Furthermore, Marrielos Porras lists some of the possibilities: Are there any things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why are you doing it on the Internet?
Or would you like it if someone posted your photo the way you posted your friend's photo?
Do you know what the others publish about you?
When you mark people in photos of the celebration, did you ask these people for permission?
And one more thing: does everyone always need to know what you're doing?
The next point is to make them realize that they must behave in the Internet environment as well as outside it.
They're the same rules.
"A person outside the Internet is guided by respect, morals and other principles, and this should be the same on social networks," he claims.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, a first-degree teacher and an educational counselor explains that it is essential that parents of children read the rules of social networks carefully.
"If they understand every monstrosity, they have a good basis to talk to children about the consequences that an account can have.
